      <hedline>
        <hl1>When Politics Is a Family Affair</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Marion Goldin letter says roles fathers have played in lives of Gov George W Bush and Vice Pres Al Gore should be celebrated as expression of family values (July 28 Editorial Observer)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Presidential Campaign as Oedipal Arena,'' by Howell Raines (Editorial Observer, July 28):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Presidential Campaign as Oedipal Arena,'' by Howell Raines (Editorial Observer, July 28):</p>
        <p>I continue to be surprised at how many observers of this presidential race put the father-son relationships of the Bushes and the Gores in the negative column. Isn't this something that should rank high on the list of positives? Shouldn't we be encouraging close and continuing ties between father and son? Should George W. Bush and Al Gore be deprived of the knowledge gained by the successes and failures of their parents' decades of public service?</p>
        <p>As a country we have seen the cost and consequences of absentee fathers and nonexistent role models for our children. Let us celebrate the roles their fathers have played in the lives of George W. Bush and Al Gore. If this isn't what family values are all about, what is?</p>
        <p>MARION GOLDIN  Washington, July 28, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
